  "location": "Zandvoort, North Holland",
  "event_preview": "Circuit Zandvoort is a 4.259 km (2.646 mi) permanent road course in Zandvoort, North Holland, Netherlands, opened in 1948 and hosting Formula One's Dutch Grand Prix since 2021. The 2026 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters round at Zandvoort takes place 22-24 May 2026 as the championship's second round. The circuit's 14 corners are built around dramatic high-speed sections interspersed with heavy braking zones, creating a layout that demands commitment and rewards precision in equal measure.\n\nDTM returned to Zandvoort in 2023 after a five-year absence, with the circuit now featuring revised banking that altered lap times significantly from the pre-2020 configuration. The Mercedes-AMG package showed strength at Zandvoort during that 2023 return, and BMW's Schubert Motorsport will seek to build on momentum from a competitive start to the season at Red Bull Ring. Porsche's Thomas Preining and his Manthey EMA teammates return to action after the Austrian season opener, while Lucas Auer and the Mercedes-AMG contingent will look to extend their early-season form in front of Dutch spectators.\n\nThe DTM qualifying lap record at Zandvoort is 1:32.585, set by Maro Engel driving a Mercedes AMG GT3 during qualifying in 2023. The DTM race lap record is 1:34.371, set by Ricardo Feller driving an Audi R8 LMS GT3 in the second race of the 2023 weekend.",
